# Venture Audit Google Form Documentation

## Purpose

The Google Form Implementation provides arguably the easiest implementation of the venture audit, the idea here being that the Form can allow a person to easily set up a venture audit, easily view the results using a Google Form, and allow respondents to get a radar chart with their information.

Note: The person who does these steps will be the sender of the email with the radar chart to the respondents. For example, if John Doe does the steps below and Jane Smith fills out the form, Jane Smith will receive an email from John Doe. There are not any issues with John Doe making the form and filling it out; in that case the sender and receiver will be the same.

## Setup

### Step 1: Create a Google Form

Go into Google Drive and create a Google Form.

### Step 2: Add Email Collection

Obviously, emails are needed in order to send the spider charts. To do this, go to the “Settings” tab, then under “Responses”, change “Collect email addresses” to “Responder input”. This means google will assure that the person enters a valid email address, but they don’t need to be logged into Google in order to complete the quiz.

### Step 3: Fill in the Google Form with Your Questions

### Step 4: Under the “Responses” tab, Click “View Google Sheet”

### Step 5: Add Sheets

Now in the Google Sheet, notice how in the bottom left a sheet called “Form Responses 1” should be highlighted. Next to it, click a “+” icon on three sheets called: “Forms Condensed”, “Reference: Answers”, “Generate Chart”.

### Step 6: Fill out “Reference: Answers” sheet

In row 1, fill in 5 cells with the following (in order): “Category”, “Question”, “Answer”, “Code”, Weight”. In the category, put what category the question calls under (ex. Business Method Levels or Product/Service Levels). Under Questions, put every question from the Google Form, though note for each question you must put every option in the Answer column. This means that if a question has 3 possible options, the question should appear in 3 rows for each answer option. For the Code, this is not used yet due to the requirements, but is meant to create an easy way to expand the project if there is a desire to compare answers, since some questions are asked more to assure that the venture is as developed as they claim. 

The Weight is how much the Answer affects the Category. For Yes answers, this will probably be 1, for No answers this will probably be 0\.

The point with this sheet is to provide a no code way to update the chart based on the form.
